Descriptions & Prompts

 Purpose
This custom GPT is designed to generate detailed prompts and physical descriptions for creating realistic AI-generated portraits in ComfyUI. It is especially useful for workflows involving Flux.1, LoRA training, or any context where character consistency is critical.

 Key Features
Structured character design:
Generate consistent facial descriptions including:

Face shape, bone structure, skin texture

Eye shape and color, nose, lips, jawline

Hairstyle, volume, length, and color

Expression and gaze direction

Photographic realism vocabulary:
Tailored for diffusion models with phrasing optimized for ComfyUI, SD1.5/XL, and Flux.1 pipelines

Multiple output modes:

Standard description for prompting

Technical breakdown for precise visual replication

Add-on style and lighting variants

 Integration in Your Workflow
When generating a new character portrait, always start with this GPT to define:

Who the model is (gender, ethnicity-neutral, or custom)

Visual traits and desired aesthetics

Special features (e.g. freckles, almond eyes, square jaw)

Copy and paste the generated prompt into the CLIP Text Encode node inside your ComfyUI workflow.

 Redux as a Generation Guide
If you use the Redux node as guidance in your generation pipeline (e.g., via Guide (Redux) or ReduxConditioning), this GPT becomes even more powerful.

The character description it generates will be used in combination with Reduxs persistent guidance system, ensuring that:

Identity and facial structure are preserved across generations

The subject is rendered consistently in different poses, angles, or lighting setups

Prompt conditioning remains anchored by Reduxs latent control logic

Auto-Detailer (SAM + Inpaint)  Face / Skin / Eyes / Hands Refinement

Use this module to detect and selectively inpaint specific facial or body zones such as hands, eyes, lips, skin, hair using SAM segmentation and targeted prompts.

 Recommended Settings

guide_size: 512

max_size: 1024 or higher

steps: 2030

cfg: 1.01.5

sampler_name: euler / dpm++

denoise: 0.100.20 (higher will overwrite detail!)

noise_mask: enabled

force_inpaint: enabled

bbox_threshold: 0.5

sam_threshold: 0.93 or higher

bbox_crop_factor: 2.53.0

feather: 510

drop_size: 10

 Denoise  Most Critical Parameter

0.050.2: Best for fine corrections, detail preservation

>0.4: Destroys original features  use only for full reconstruction

 Keywords to Guide Detection / Prompting

Skin: skin-tone, pores, freckles, smooth-skin, natural-texture

Eyes: eyes, iris, eyelashes, gaze, pupil

Hands: hands, fingers, palm, pose, hand-shape

Hair: hairline, hair-strands, curly-hair, layered-hair, shiny-hair

Lips: mouth, lips, lip-gloss, natural-lips, defined-lips

 Tips

Pair low denoise with high sam_threshold for consistent results

Use bbox_crop_factor > 2.5 to include edge context

Mask feathering helps avoid sharp cutlines (use 510)

Latent Noise Injection  Adjustable Parameters (Portrait Master Workflow)
This control group allows for precise fine-tuning of the latent space upscale and reconstruction phase, enhancing the balance between facial detail fidelity, consistency, and photorealism. It is especially effective when generating training images for LoRA, AI influencers, or virtual talent.

1. Latent Upscale (range: 1.0  2.0)
Function:
Controls the scale factor in the latent space before decoding. It directly affects perceived sharpness and output resolution adaptation.

Usage tips:

1.0: preserves original latent scale (neutral)

1.251.5: enhances fine skin details (ideal for portraits)

>1.6: may introduce artifacts or distortions

Recommended for face rendering: 1.25

2. Flux Guidance
Function:
Controls the strength of Flux.1 guidance in the image refinement process. A higher value enforces structure and identity retention, especially for character consistency.

Usage tips:

1.0: soft guidance, more creative freedom

1.52.0: stronger structural coherence

>2.0: may stiffen natural details

Suggested range: 1.82.0 for consistent AI faces

3. Denoise (default 0.55)
Function:
Sets the denoising strength. Higher values regenerate more content, which may alter facial identity if pushed too far.

Usage tips:

0.30.4: minimal changes, preserves details

0.50.6: balanced noise removal and detail retention

>0.7: may overprocess skin or identity features

Ideal for high-fidelity faces: 0.55

4. Speed  Accuracy (default 0.50)
Function:
Balances generation speed vs. detail accuracy. Especially relevant for optimized or hybrid processing nodes.

Usage tips:

0.0: fastest, low detail

1.0: best quality, slower

0.60.8: good compromise for previews

Recommended for final renders: 1.0

5. Sharpen (default 0.00)
Function:
Applies post-process latent sharpening to enhance edge clarity, especially in facial features.

Usage tips:

0.0: off (default)

0.10.3: enhances eyes and lips

>0.4: risk of over-sharpening or artifacting

Suggested use: 0.10.2 when faces appear too soft

6. Rough  Smooth (default 0.60)
Function:
Adjusts skin texture smoothness. Lower values produce raw textures; higher values deliver soft, editorial-style looks.

Usage tips:

0.4: more raw, gritty skin texture

0.60.7: balanced and natural

0.81.0: beauty-pass effect, good for AI influencers

Ideal for soft editorial portraits: 0.650.75

7. Noise Strength (default 0.30)
Function:
Injects controlled latent noise into the generation process, increasing creative variability and breaking rigidity.

Usage tips:

0.10.2: low variability, high fidelity

0.30.4: good balance for dataset generation

>0.5: use for stylized or cinematic effects

Recommended for LoRA training: 0.30

Detail Sampling & Distribution Tuning (MXToolkit  Advanced Controls)
These two parameters are designed for fine-grain control of how the image is sampled and refined during the latent diffusion process. They act as post-sampling filters that subtly adjust texture rendering, structural balance, and noise behavior.

1. Detail Demon Sampler (suggested: 0.10)
Function:
Injects a controlled micro-detail emphasis layer during sampling. Enhances texture fidelity in facial regions such as skin pores, eyelashes, hair strands, or fabric edges.

Usage tips:
0.00: off  no enhancement
0.030.07: soft texture boost
0.080.12: stronger detail pop
>0.15: risk of artificial noise in smooth skin or over-sharpening

Recommended for high-resolution portrait faces: 0.050.10

Note: Works best when paired with moderate sharpening and denoise (e.g. denoise = 0.55, sharpen = 0.1)

2. Advanced Lying Sigma Sampler (suggested: -0.06)
Function:
Applies a statistical rebalancing layer to the latent noise field by adjusting sigma deviation behavior. This controls the lying components of the diffusion distribution, effectively minimizing overexposed or uneven texture zones.

Usage tips:

0.00: no correction
-0.02 to -0.06: gently reduces unwanted haloing or texture bleed
-0.08 or lower: useful for highly stylized, cinematic results, but may reduce realism
Recommended value for clean photorealism: -0.05 to -0.06

Note: Has cumulative effects with Noise Strength and Smoothness. Fine-tuning all three ensures maximum skin clarity and visual harmony.

Seed Control  rgthree-comfy
The seed is a numerical value that initializes the random generation process in your diffusion model. It acts like the starting point of image generation: the same seed + same prompt = nearly identical output.

 How to Use It Effectively
 When you find a generation you like, disable randomization to lock the seed. This allows you to produce similar images with minor prompt or LoRA variations.

 Use "Use Last Queued Seed" to keep the most recent one, especially useful in iterative refinement workflows.

 Portraits & Seed Behavior in Flux1
In Flux1 workflows, certain seed values tend to generate:

Very close-up portraits

Unnatural neck proportions (elongated or compressed)

Cropped foreheads or heads out of frame

Why?
Because the seed influences the initial noise pattern in the latent space, some seeds naturally favor zoomed-in compositions or distorted facial geometry due to how the noise aligns with facial symmetry during diffusion.

 Tip
Once you find a well-framed, well-proportioned face with a specific seed, reuse it across multiple prompt variations to keep character consistency and framing stable.

If you're getting consistent deformities: change seed + reduce denoise slightly.

 Understanding the Role of Seeds in AI Image Generation
In AI-driven image generation, a seed is a numerical value that initializes the random number generator, setting the starting conditions for the creation process. This seed determines the initial noise pattern from which the image is developed. Using the same seed with identical prompts and settings will consistently produce the same image, ensuring reproducibility. Conversely, altering the seed introduces variability, leading to different outputs even with the same prompt.

 How Seeds Affect Image Characteristics
Seeds influence various aspects of the generated image, including:

Composition and Layout: The arrangement of elements within the image can vary significantly with different seeds.

Color and Texture: Seeds can affect the color palette and texture details, leading to variations in the image's mood and feel.

Lighting and Shadows: The interplay of light and shadow can change, impacting the image's depth and realism.

These effects stem from the seed's role in determining the initial noise, which guides the diffusion process in generating the final image.

 Best Practices for Seed Utilization
To harness the power of seeds effectively:

Locking the Seed: Once a desirable image is generated, note the seed value and reuse it to produce consistent results across multiple iterations or variations.

Exploring Variations: To discover new compositions or styles, experiment with different seed values while keeping other parameters constant.

Documenting Seeds: Maintain a record of seed values that yield favorable results for future reference and reproducibility.

 Considerations Specific to Flux1
Within the Flux1 model, certain seed values may consistently produce specific characteristics:

Close-Up Portraits: Some seeds tend to generate tightly cropped facial images.

Distorted Features: High seed values might lead to unnatural proportions, such as elongated necks or skewed facial features.

These tendencies are due to how the initial noise pattern interacts with the model's training data and architecture. Adjusting the seed can mitigate such issues, leading to more balanced and natural images.

 Discovering Effective Seed Values
While there isn't a universal list of "best" seed values, some communities and studies have identified seeds that consistently produce high-quality images. For instance, research has shown that certain seeds can lead to better image fidelity and composition. Exploring forums, repositories, and academic papers can provide insights into such seed values.

This segment of the workflow is designed to automatically detect, mask, and refine the chin area using advanced segmentation, cropping, and targeted LoRA application. It is ideal for improving facial symmetry, correcting underdeveloped chins, or ensuring character consistency across generated images.

 Modules Description
1. SegmentAnything + DINO (SAM + GroundingDINO)
Purpose:
Performs automatic object detection and segmentation using SAM v1 with enhanced bounding box guidance from GroundingDINO.

Key settings:

threshold: 0.30  controls object sensitivity

detail_method: VITMatte  high-precision mask extraction

black_point / white_point: defines mask range

process_detail: true: enables high-detail mode

 Used here to precisely isolate the chin area for editing.

2. LayerMask: SegmentAnythingUltra V3 (Advance)
Purpose:
Generates a high-resolution mask of the selected area (chin) with customizable dilation/erosion parameters.

Enhancements:

Supports CUDA processing

max_megapixels: 2.0 ensures lightweight mask generation without quality loss

3. Inpaint Crop (Improved)
Purpose:
Crops the masked chin area and resizes it for inpainting using a high-quality bicubic upscale. Ensures pixel-level precision and proper mask handling.

Key settings:

mask_fill_holes: true

mask_expand_pixels: 5

mask_blend_pixels: 32

context_from_mask_extend_factor: 1.25  includes surrounding chin area for seamless inpainting

output_resize_to_target_size: true (1024x1024 target)

4. LoRA Injection  Chin Refinement

 Chin Fixer 2000  LoRA on Civitai

LayerStyle Color Pipeline  Exposure / Grain / Contrast / LUT
This module chain allows you to perform final image grading with tools commonly used in film post-production and photography. It adds cinematic grain, contrast control, and precise color grading via LUTs (Look-Up Tables).

 Included Nodes Overview
1. LayerColor: Exposure
Adjusts global brightness. Use values from -1.0 to +1.0 depending on scene balance.
 Typical: 0.0

2. LayerFilter: Add Grain
Simulates analog film grain.

grain_power: 0.20

grain_scale: 0.4

grain_sat: 0.75

3. LayerColor: Brightness Contrast V2
Adjusts post-exposure balance:

brightness: 1.00

contrast: 1.10

saturation: 0.95

4. LayerColor: LUT Apply
Applies cinematic color grading using .cube LUTs.

LUT: Fuji_Astia.cube

color_space: linear or srgb

strength: 0100%

 Where to Install LUT Files in ComfyUI
Save your .cube LUT files in the following path:

swift
Copia
Modifica
ComfyUI/custom_nodes/comfyui-layerstyle/luts/
Once added, they will appear in the dropdown inside the LayerColor: LUT Apply node. You may need to restart ComfyUI after adding new files.
